<a id=Parent_Processing></a>

1. Align parental reads (uniquely with 3 mismatch) to parental references (consensed sequences)¶

This step first uses bowtie to align reads and then any multiply-mapped reads and unmapped reads get passed to Last which will also attempt to uniquely align reads. Only those reads that align uniquely will be used for HSE.

Scripts:¶

align_reads_to_Crocifolius_consensed_bt_last.sbatch
align_reads_to_Lamottei_consensed_bt_last.sbatch

Dependencies:¶

identify_quality.py
SeparateLast.py
parse_last_sam_v2.pl
maf-convert.py

Program Versions:¶

bowtie/0.12.9
last/531
python/2.7.3

Input:¶

Design file:
    DESIGN + trago_hybrids_with_reps.txt
Refs: 
    PROJ + Lamottei_post_compression_contigs.renamed.fasta
    PROJ + Crocifolius_post_compression_contigs.renamed.fasta
Reads:
    PROJ + /original_data/

Output:¶

PROJ + /alignment_output/{SP}_{REP}_uniq_2_{REF}.sam # Ex. Lamottei_1_uniq_2_Lam.sam

2. Filter SAM files that don't fall within features in BED file¶

--Memory reduced from 160G on bigmem to 5G on HPG2. I'm not sure why the memory requirements were so large.
--After running, there is an intermediate bash script to run:
/ufrc/barbazuk/lboat/T.lamottei_T.crocifolius/Complete_data_set/align_reads_for_samcompare/filter_sam_files/filtered_parent_sam_files/rename_filtered_files.bash

In the previous step, we wanted to align to the entire transcriptome to prevent reads from mapping greedily to spurious locations in the transcriptome. Here, we isolate reads that map within our Common Orthologous REgions (COREs) so that we can make comparisons between reference mappings.

Scripts:¶

filter_sam_files_parents_2_parents_v3.sbatch

Dependencies:¶

PROJ + /scripts/sam-filter-by-bed.pl

Program Versions:¶

perl/5.16.0

    PROJ + /alignment_output/{SP}_{REP}_uniq_2_{REF}.sam
Bed:
    PROJ + /filter_sam_files/{SP}_overlaps_WRT_orthologs.renamed.bed

Output:¶

PROJ + /filter_sam_files/filtered_parent_sam_files/{SP}_{REP}_uniq_2_Lam_filter_for_Cast.sam 
PROJ + /filter_sam_files/filtered_parent_sam_files/{SP}_{REP}_uniq_2_Croc_filter_for_Cast.sam
    # Ex. LAM_1_uniq_2_Lam.sam -- changed due to 32 char max length

14. Flag Significant Bayesian Poisson-Gamma Output¶

Flag those putative orthologous pairs that exhibit mapping bias. Flag significant if the 
    credible interval [similar to 95% Highest posterior density interval (HPDI)] does not overlap 0.5 
    for each prior (q4,q5,q6). 

Then, flag significant for all three if q4 = q5 = q6 = 1

Scripts:¶

execute_bayesian_flag_sig_results_parents.bash

Dependencies:¶

bayesian_flag_sig_results_parents_pdf.sas

Program Versions:¶

sas/9.4 (originally 9.3 but due to licensing, this must be updated accordingly)

Input:¶

empirical_bayesian_parents_output/PG_emp_bayesian_results_{SP}_parents.csv

Output:¶

empirical_bayesian_parents_output/PG_emp_bayesian_results_{SP}_parents_flag_sig.csv

$\bar\theta$ plots:¶

  • $\bar\theta$ represents mapping bias for Reads onto Lam or Croc
  • Contain histogram of $\bar\theta$ values
  • Contain kernel density lines -- which represent a non-parametric way to estimate the probability density function of the $\bar\theta$ values
  • 0 == Line == T. lamottei
  • 1 == Tester == T.crocifolius

Polyploid Alignment and Quantification¶

Notes on differences between parents and polyploid analyses:¶

- We have 4 independent T. castellanus polyploids with 3 bioreps each
- We really only have 1 population for both T. lamottei and T. crocifolius
- We need to assess HSE in each T. castellanus population separately
- NOTE: We have parents and polyploid P-B + P-II = IIb --> we should assess HSE specially for these

def filter_csv(file_name):
    """Given flagged bayesian output in CSV format, isolate unbiased loci. 
    This is only meant for the parents, as the parent data can biasedly map to its own reference or exhibit no bias."""
    import pandas as pd
    import numpy as np
    df = pd.read_csv(file_name, index_col = "commonID")
    cols = list(df.columns)
    sig_col = cols[-1]
    reads=sig_col.split("_")[2]
    unbiased_loci = []
    print("\tDF pre-filter: " + str(len(df.index)))
    if reads == "Lam":
        # identify loci not biased toward Croc
        not_biased = df[(df[sig_col] == 0) & (df["q5_mean_theta"] <= 0.75)]
        print("\t\tNot biased: " + str(len(not_biased.index)))
        df = pd.concat([df[(df["q5_mean_theta"] <= 0.5) & (df[sig_col] == 1)],not_biased])
    elif reads == "Croc":
        # identify loci not biased toward Lam
        not_biased = df[(df[sig_col] == 0) & (df["q5_mean_theta"] >= 0.25)]
        print("\t\tNot biased: " + str(len(not_biased.index)))
        df = pd.concat([df[(df["q5_mean_theta"] >= 0.5) & (df[sig_col] == 1)], not_biased])
    print("\tDF post-filter: " + str(len(df.index)))
    return df

def inline_hist(df, file_name):
    """Inline plot histogram of q5 mean theta"""
    plt.figure()
    plt.hist(df["q5_mean_theta"])
    plt.title(file_name + " q0.5 mean theta")
    plt.xlabel("Theta")
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.show()

def csv_to_df(file_name):
    """Given flagged bayesian output in CSV format, convert to standard dataframe. 
    This is only meant for the hybrid, as the hybrid data may biasedly express one ortholog over another."""
    import pandas as pd
    import numpy as np
    df = pd.read_csv(file_name, index_col = "commonID")
    cols = list(df.columns)
    cols[-1]="sig_all_three"
    df.columns = cols
    print("Length of dataframe pre-filter: " + str(len(df["sig_all_three"])))
    return df
In [14]:
def hist_unfiltered_filtered(df, unbiased_loci):
    """Plot a histogram of both the unfiltered and filtered q5 mean theta to visualize filtering"""
    import numpy as np
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.figure()
    unbiased_df = df[df.index.isin(unbiased_loci)]
    print("\tLoci exhibiting HSE pre-filter: " + str(np.sum(df["sig_all_three"])))
    n, bins, patches = plt.hist(df["q5_mean_theta"], bins=50, histtype='step', facecolor='r', label='pre-filter')
    print("Total loci post-filter: " + str(len(unbiased_df["sig_all_three"])))
    print("\tLoci exhibiting HSE post-filter: " + str(np.sum(unbiased_df["sig_all_three"])))
    n, bins, patches = plt.hist(unbiased_df["q5_mean_theta"], bins=50, histtype='step', facecolor='b', label='post-filter')

    plt.xlabel('Mean Theta')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Distribution of Mean Theta for T. castellanus')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8.0, 8.0)
    plt.show()
    return unbiased_df

3. Identify putative homeolog loss¶

This step identifies putative homeolog loss from the set of unbiased contigs. The set is first filtered by looking at homeolog pairs where one reference has zero reads. Then, there must be HSE toward the parent with data (i.e. the posterior may not overlap theta 0.5).

%%writefile /ufrc/barbazuk/lboat/T.lamottei_T.crocifolius/Complete_data_set/align_reads_for_samcompare/scripts/putative_homeolog_loss.py
"""
Created on Tue May  9 13:48:20 2017

@author: Lucas Boatwright
"""

from sys import argv, stderr
import argparse
from datetime import datetime
import pandas as pd

def parse_arguments():
    """Parse arguments passed to script"""
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=
    "This script is designed to check for putative loss between homeologs \
    \nusing counts from homeolog COREs used in the PG analysis.\n\n \
    Example: python {0} -c ase_bayes_Cast2_lam_croc_flag.csv -b bayes_flag_sig_Cast2.csv".format(argv[0]),
    formatter_class = argparse.RawDescriptionHelpFormatter)
    
    requiredNamed = parser.add_argument_group('required arguments')

    requiredNamed.add_argument("-c", "--COUNTS", type=str, required=True,
    help="Bayes flagged CSV of read counts for Line and Tester", action="store")
    
    requiredNamed.add_argument("-b", "--BIAS", type=str, required=True,
    help="Bayes flagged CSV of loci demonstrating HSE", action="store")

    return parser.parse_args() 
    

def find_putative_loss(file_name):
    """Given file name, determine loci that are putatively lost based upon lack of expression"""
    df = pd.read_csv(file_name)
    output_base = file_name.split(".csv")[0]
    df["Line_mean"] = df[["LINE_TOTAL_1","LINE_TOTAL_2","LINE_TOTAL_3"]
                            ].mean(axis=1)
    df["Line_std"] = df[["LINE_TOTAL_1","LINE_TOTAL_2","LINE_TOTAL_3"]
                            ].std(axis=1)
    df["Tester_mean"] = df[["TESTER_TOTAL_1","TESTER_TOTAL_2","TESTER_TOTAL_3"]
                            ].mean(axis=1)
    df["Tester_std"]=df[["TESTER_TOTAL_1","TESTER_TOTAL_2","TESTER_TOTAL_3"]
                            ].std(axis=1)
    
    df["Line_zero"] = ((df["Tester_mean"] > 0 ) & (df["Line_mean"] == 0 ))
    df["Tester_zero"] = ((df["Line_mean"] > 0 ) & (df["Tester_mean"] == 0 ))      

    return df

    
def verify_HSE(df, hse_file):
    """Verify that each locus does not overlap 0.5 based upon 95% HDI"""
    flag_sig = pd.read_csv(hse_file)
    sig_true = flag_sig.columns[-1]
    merged_df = pd.merge(df, flag_sig)    
    output_df = merged_df[["commonID","Line_zero","Tester_zero","Line_mean","Tester_mean",sig_true]]
    lost = output_df[(output_df[sig_true]==1) & (output_df["Line_zero"] | output_df["Tester_zero"])]
    output_base = hse_file.split(".csv")[0] + "_putative_loss.csv"
    lost.to_csv(output_base, index=False)
    
    
if __name__ == "__main__":
    start = datetime.now()
    args = parse_arguments()
    stderr.write("Executed: python {0} -c {1} -b {2}\n".format(argv[0],args.COUNTS, args.BIAS))
    df = find_putative_loss(args.COUNTS)
    verify_HSE(df, args.BIAS)
    stop = datetime.now()
    stderr.write("Runtime: {0}\n".format(str(stop - start)))
